# Matrix Multiplication Loop Permutation Study (N = 512)

## Objective

Investigate how loop ordering affects the performance of matrix multiplication on a row-major architecture by keeping the arithmetic operation identical while changing only the traversal pattern through memory.

The experiment was performed using:

* Matrix size: **512 × 512**
* Data type: `int`
* Three matrices: `A`, `B`, and `C`
* Row-major memory layout (C language)
* Execution time measured using `clock_gettime()`

The multiplication computed was:

[
C[i][j] += A[i][k] \times B[k][j]
]

---

## Results

| Loop Order | Inner Loop | Register Reuse      | Execution Time (s) |
| ---------- | ---------- | ------------------- | -----------------: |
| IJK        | k          | No                  |           0.232152 |
| IKJ        | j          | Yes (`r = A[i][k]`) |       **0.142534** |
| JIK        | k          | No                  |           0.228326 |
| JKI        | i          | Yes (`r = B[k][j]`) |           0.237951 |
| KIJ        | j          | Yes (`r = A[i][k]`) |           0.149822 |
| KJI        | i          | Yes (`r = B[k][j]`) |           0.235154 |

