## Interpretation

Although all six implementations perform exactly the same mathematical computation:

[
C_{ij} = \sum_k A_{ik}B_{kj}
]

their performance differs significantly because the order of traversal changes how efficiently the CPU accesses memory.

---

## Why IKJ and KIJ Are Fast

These orders make the innermost loop iterate over `j`.

This produces:

### Matrix B

```
B[k][0], B[k][1], B[k][2], ...
```

which corresponds to contiguous row traversal in row-major memory.

---

### Matrix C

```
C[i][0], C[i][1], C[i][2], ...
```

which is also contiguous.

---

### Register Reuse

A single element

```
A[i][k]
```

is loaded once:

```c
int r = A[i][k];
```

and reused throughout the entire inner loop.

This minimizes memory traffic and maximizes register utilization.

---

## Why IJK and JIK Are Slower

The innermost loop iterates over `k`.

For matrix B, the access pattern becomes:

```
B[0][j]
B[1][j]
B[2][j]
...
```

which walks down a column.

Because matrices are stored row-by-row in memory, this causes repeated jumps across memory locations.

Consequences:

* Poor spatial locality
* Increased cache misses
* Reduced effectiveness of hardware prefetchers

---

## Why JKI and KJI Are Slowest

The innermost loop iterates over `i`.

This causes accesses such as:

```
A[0][k]
A[1][k]
A[2][k]
...
```

and

```
C[0][j]
C[1][j]
C[2][j]
...
```

which both move vertically through row-major matrices.

As a result:

* Multiple matrices suffer from poor locality simultaneously.
* Cache lines are underutilized.
* Memory latency dominates execution.

---

## Key Observation

The arithmetic performed by all six versions is identical.

The only difference is:

```
How data moves through memory.
```

This experiment demonstrates that:

> Matrix multiplication performance is often determined less by the number of multiplications and additions, and more by how effectively the algorithm exploits the memory hierarchy.

---

## Memory Hierarchy Insight

Performance optimization occurs across several layers:

```
Arithmetic Operations
        ↓
Register Reuse
        ↓
L1 Cache Locality
        ↓
L2/L3 Cache Locality
        ↓
Main Memory Access
```

Changing loop order does not alter the arithmetic workload.

Instead, it changes how efficiently these layers are utilized.

---

## Final Conclusion

For row-major systems:

```
IKJ ≈ KIJ
    ↓
IJK ≈ JIK
    ↓
JKI ≈ KJI
```

Loop permutations that:

* stream horizontally through memory,
* maximize register reuse, and
* reuse cache lines effectively,

deliver significantly better performance despite producing exactly the same mathematical result.
